               <floruit>5thC</floruit>
               <note xml:id="d2e48098" n="50"> For this form see
                                vol. 1, under Samuel (3) B/M, p. 215. On the interchange of <span xml:lang="checkme"></span> with <span xml:lang="checkme"></span> in Greek orthography see vol.
                                1, Introduction 2.3.3.2, p. 22.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e48114" n="51"> Slightly
                                north-east of Damascus.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e48128" n="52"> The suggestion that
                                this is a Jewish inscription is based, 1. On the formula <span xml:lang="checkme"></span> (God is one), but see
                                Introduction 6.1.6; 2. The biblical name Samuel (35) is found in the
                                inscription, but he could be Christian, see vol. 3, Introduction
                                6.6.7, p. 52; 3. However, the name of his brother, Tanḥum, was
                                clearly Jewish, see Introduction 6.2.2.4.</note>
            </person>
